===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[obtain]] or [[receive]] (something) from something else.
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2013|month=July-August|author=[http://www.americanscientist.org/authors/detail/sarah-glaz Sarah Glaz]
|title=[http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/pub/2013/4/ode-to-prime-numbers Ode to Prime Numbers]
|volume=101|issue=4|magazine={{w|American Scientist}}
|passage=Some poems, echoing the purpose of early poetic treatises on scientific principles, attempt to elucidate the mathematical concepts that underlie prime numbers. Others play with primes’ cultural associations. Still others '''derive''' their structure from mathematical patterns involving primes.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|logic}} To [[deduce]] (a [[conclusion]]) by [[reasoning]].
# {{lb|en|transitive|linguistics}} To find the [[derivation]] of (a [[word]] or [[phrase]]).
# {{lb|en|transitive|chemistry}} To [[create]] (a [[compound]]) from another by means of a [[reaction]].
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[originate]] or [[stem]] (from).
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2012-01
|author=Robert M. Pringle|volume=100|issue=1|page=31|magazine={{w|American Scientist}}
|title=[http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/2012/1/how-to-be-manipulative How to Be Manipulative]
|passage=As in much of biology, the most satisfying truths in ecology '''derive''' from manipulative experimentation. Tinker with nature and quantify how it responds.}}
#: {{ux|en|her excellent organisation skills '''derive''' from her time as a secretary in the army}}
# To turn the course of (water, etc.); to [[divert]] and distribute into subordinate channels.
#* {{RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World}} Book 33
#*: For fear it [water] choke up the pits{{...}}they [the workman] '''deriue''' it by other drains.

